##CNN: Britain is betting big, and no one knows if it will work

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

Source: Observer, Zhang Chenjing

The sudden global outbreak of a new coronavirus crisis is testing the capacity of different countries to govern. And China, Italy and other countries to respond to different, the United Kingdom chose to directly "flat" , the so-called "group Immunization" plan, shocked all sectors.

In response, CNN said on the 14th, this is the British government's gamble, no one knows whether it will work, only time will tell. But there is no doubt that the new coronavirus crisis must be Prime Minister Johnson's worst nightmare.

The editor in chief of the Lancet, a leading British journal, took to twitter to attack the situation, calling it a "roulette wheel" of public safety and a grave mistake. He calls on governments to share the scientific evidence, Data and models on which their policies are based.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
British Prime Minister Johnson, seen in this screenshot

As of April 14,347 new cases of pneumonia had been diagnosed in the UK, bringing the total to 1,145. There were 10 new deaths and a total of 21 deaths.

In the face of such a severe epidemic, the United Kingdom did not like China, Italy, or other European countries, to take strict prevention and control measures, but to take moderate measures, announced the outbreak response measures from the "containment" phase into the "mitigation" phase.

At this stage, the British government changed the way it tests people who show mild symptoms to focus on those with more severe symptoms, and recommended that people with mild symptoms such as cough and fever be isolated at home for seven days, do not call an ambulance unless the condition worsens;

In addition, schools are not being closed in the UK, only being advised to stop organising international travel, and people over 70 who are in poor health should not travel on cruises.

British officials have repeatedly said they acted on the advice of scientific experts. It is also claimed that, based on current scientific research, it would be beneficial for the country in the long run to establish a population immunity to the new coronavirus.

Government scientists also defended the move, saying they had found that for patients with no health problems, the new coronavirus usually causes only mild symptoms for up to five days. But in the elderly and infirm, it triggers an immune response that causes many fatal injuries.

Experts also believe the government's latest move will ease pressure on hospitals by delaying the peak season of new pneumonia from April, the traditional flu season, to the summer.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chief Scientific Adviser to the British government

CNN: Britain is betting big

However, these practices have caused great controversy. CNN reported that the British Intensive Care Unit doctors have issued a warning, if the number of confirmed cases reached a peak, there may be a lack of suction and other conditions. If doctors and nurses are also infected, the situation will be exacerbated by a severe shortage of staff.

Jeremy Hunt, the former health secretary, is concerned: We have only four weeks to get to where Italy is and we have done nothing.

WHO spokeswoman Margaret Harriss questioned plans for "herd immunity" , saying each virus acts differently in the body and stimulates a different immune system. "We can talk about theory, but at the moment we are in a real situation and we have to think about taking action. ".

In recent days, Richard Holden, editor in chief of the Lancet, a leading British journal, has posted several tweets attacking Britain's response to the outbreak. He accused the British government of making a grave mistake by playing "Roulette" with the public's safety rather than basing its decisions on science.

Richard said he was one of a number of British public health experts who published an open letter in The Times on Sunday saying the UK's approach to the epidemic was markedly different from that of most countries and that there was no indication, the British decision is based on the experience of other countries to contain the virus, the British government called on the basis of decision-making, data, models.

"without complete openness, there is a loss of public trust, " Richard said, adding that such transparency was essential to maintaining understanding, cooperation and trust between the scientific community, the medical community and the public.

On the same day, hundreds of scientists sent two open letters to the British government, expressing concern about its policies and calling for urgent measures such as greater social distance in the UK.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
CNN explained that the UK did not take the "social alienation" measure because its experts predicted that the epidemic peak would not come until 14 weeks later, and people were reluctant to change their lifestyles for it, than follow the new rules for more than three months.

Richard argues that the government underestimates the public's ability to understand and act. He also stressed that he was not being alarmist and that what was happening in Italy was real. And the British government is not ready for that. He also called for immediate and decisive measures such as "closure of the city" .

But there is also support for Britain's policy response. Clare Wenham, a professor at the London School of Economics, said: We don't have enough evidence that closing schools will stop the spread of the new coronavirus, but Johnson is listening to experts and has taken a fairly cautious approach. "It is a gamble indeed. ".

She said the government's top priority was to avoid public panic and ensure public co-operation in prevention and control measures, "if it's wrong, it's a political gamble" .

Downing Street seems to think that, in the long run, the panic caused by the new coronavirus may be more dangerous than the virus itself, CNN reported. No one knows whether this "Nothing in Common" gamble will work, only time will tell.

This time, the new coronavirus crisis is Johnson's worst nightmare and presents him with a unique dilemma, the report said. As Johnson grapples with the crisis, Britain's next deadline for leaving the European Union is counting down to July 1st.

According to the agreement, the transition period will last only until the end of this year. If Britain and the European Union do not make substantive progress on the negotiations by July 1, the two sides will decide on whether to extend the interim period on July 1.

The report questioned whether Johnson would risk shortages of food, medicine and other supplies to save face if talks with the European Union were slowed by the outbreak and no deal was reached by the end of June.

The British government is more willing to act decisively on the economic front than to deal with the epidemic. The New Chancellor of the Exchequer, Rishi Sunak, this week outlined emergency funding for public services in his first budget. The Bank of England also acted in concert, cutting interest rates and announcing stimulus measures.

The UK earlier said 5,000 to 10,000 people could have been infected with the new coronavirus because many were undiagnosed.
